{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2017}} {{Use British English|date=April 2016}} {{Infobox football biography |name = Henry Cook |image = Henry Cook 1908.jpg |image_size = 150 |caption = Cook while with [[Middlesbrough F.C.|Middlesbrough]] in 1912. |fullname = Henry Cook<ref name="Joyce" /> |birth_date = 23 October 1893 |birth_place = [[Middlesbrough]], England |death_date = {{death date and age |1917|1|9|1893|10|23|df=yes}}<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cwgc.org/find-war-dead/casualty/30870/COOK,%20HENRY|title=Casualty Details|last=Manchester|first=Reading Room|date=|website=www.cwgc.org|publisher=|access-date=28 December 2016}}</ref> |death_place = [[Maurepas, Somme|Maurepas]], France |height = |position = [[Wing half]] |years1 = |clubs1 = [[South Bank F.C.|South Bank]] |caps1 = |goals1 = |years2 = 1912–1915 |clubs2 = [[Middlesbrough F.C.|Middlesbrough]] |caps2 = 23 |goals2 = 0 |years3 = 1915–1916 |clubs3 = → [[Brentford F.C.|Brentford]] (guest) |caps3 = 10 |goals3 = 0 }} '''Henry Cook''' (23 October 1893 – 9 January 1917), sometimes known as '''Harry Cook''', was an English professional [[association football|footballer]] who played as a [[wing half]] in the [[The Football League|Football League]] for [[Middlesbrough F.C.|Middlesbrough]].<ref name="Joyce">{{cite book |title = Football League Players' Records 1888 to 1939|last = Joyce|first = Michael|publisher = Tony Brown|year = 2012|isbn = 190589161X|location = Nottingham|page = 64}}</ref> He also played for [[South Bank F.C.|South Bank]] and appeared as a guest for [[Brentford F.C.|Brentford]] during the [[First World War]].<ref name="White">{{Cite book|title=100 Years Of Brentford|last=|first=|publisher=Brentford FC|year=1989|isbn=0951526200|editor-last=White|editor-first=Eric|location=|page=363|pages=|via=}}</ref>
== Personal life == Prior to becoming a professional footballer, Cook was a teacher at Marton Road School and North Ormesby Junior Boys' School in [[Middlesbrough F.C.|Middlesbrough]] and had a wife and two children.<ref name="Bell">{{Cite web |url=http://www.mfc.co.uk/news/article/2014/081014-boro-war-heroes-on-tv-2006229.aspx |title=Boro War Heroes on TV |last=Bell |first=Graham |website=www.mfc.co.uk |access-date=14 September 2015}}</ref><ref name="Menzies">{{Cite book|title = Great War Britain Middlesbrough: Remembering 1914–18|last = Menzies|first = Paul|publisher = The History Press|year = 2014|isbn = 0752499718|location = |pages = }}</ref> During the First World War he served as a [[sergeant]] in the 12th (Service) Battalion of the [[Yorkshire Regiment]], known as the Teesside Pioneers.<ref name="Bell" /> He was wounded in early January 1917 while the battalion was engaged in road works in the vicinity of [[Maurepas, Somme]].<ref name="Rollofhonour">{{Cite web |url=http://www.ww1-yorkshires.org.uk/pdf-files/bob%20coulson/mbro-war-memorial-c.pdf |title=The Middlesbrough Roll of Honour of the Great War Names “C” |last=Coulson |first=Robert}}</ref> He died of his wounds of 9 January 1917 and is buried in Grove Town Cemetery, [[Méaulte]].<ref name="Bell" /> At the time of his death, Cook had been accepted for a [[Commissioned officers|commission]] and would have returned to England three days later to begin officer training.<ref name="Menzies" />
