'''Why U, Inc'''. is a non-profit 501(c)(3) educational organization funded by the Goldman Charitable Foundation.<ref name=whyuweb>{{cite web|url=http://www.whyu.org|title=Why U Home Page|website=Why U}}</ref> Why U is dedicated to exploration through the use of digital media, of new education paradigms for the STEM subjects: [[Science, Technology, Engineering, and Mathematics]]. Why U’s goal is to remove barriers to learning in the STEM subjects, and increase the public’s depth of knowledge of STEM.<ref name=whyuweb/>
Why U develops and provides worldwide access to free animated videos which teach fundamental concepts in math and science in an entertaining format. Why U animated videos are designed to develop conceptual knowledge rather than procedural skill, i.e., instill in the viewer an understanding of the underlying concepts of math and science rather than promoting the memorization of problem solving procedures. The prime focus is to clearly and efficiently explain the conceptual framework at the heart of mathematical and scientific subjects in a way which engages the viewer and holds their interest. Concepts are presented in the context of a dramatic and humorous setting using animated graphics designed to communicate complex ideas in an enjoyable and exciting way. As such, Why U videos are often used as collateral material in formal learning environments around the world.{{citation needed|date=March 2016}}
== Conceptual versus procedural knowledge ==
In recent years, there has been a shift in emphasis by educators from procedural to conceptual knowledge.<ref name="educom">{{cite web|last1=Schwartz|first1=J.E.|title=A Distinction Between Conceptual Knowledge and Procedural Knowledge|url=http://www.education.com/reference/article/distinction-conceptual-procedural-math/|website=Education.com|publisher=Pearson Allyn Bacon Prentice Hall}}</ref> One benefit of a strong conceptual understanding is that a person is less likely to forget concepts than procedures. “If conceptual understanding is gained, then a person can reconstruct a procedure that may have been forgotten. On the other hand, if procedural knowledge is the limit of a person's learning, there is no way to reconstruct a forgotten procedure. Conceptual understanding in mathematics, along with procedural skill, is much more powerful than procedural skill alone.”<ref name=schwartz/> “Research has shown that students in a conceptually oriented mathematics class outperform students in a procedurally oriented mathematics class on tests and on measures of attitude toward mathematics. (See, for example, Boaler, 1998; Cain, 2002; Fuson et al., 2000; Masden and Lanier, 1992.)”<ref name=schwartz>{{cite book|last1=Schwarftz|first1=James E.|title=Elementary Mathematics Pedagogical Content Knowledge: Powerful Ideas for Teachers|date=June 8, 2007|publisher=Pearson|isbn=0205493750|edition=1|url=https://www.amazon.com/gp/product/0205493750?ie=UTF8&linkCode=xm2&camp=1789&creativeASIN=0205493750}}</ref>
== History ==
Why U grew out of an earlier non-profit corporation, Wired Science. In 2001, Steve Goldman created Wired Science as a charitable endeavor to develop digital kiosks that facilitate informal learning at science centers.<ref name=obj3162002>{{cite journal|title=All Wired Up|journal=Orlando Business Journal|date=May 31 – June 6, 2002|page=27|url=http://www.stevegoldman.com/Publications/AboutWS/2002-05-31%20Business%20Digest%20-%20All%20Wired%20Up.pdf}}</ref><ref name=oscjga2002>{{cite journal|url=http://www.stevegoldman.com/Publications/AboutWS/2002-06-00%20Orlando%20Science%20Center%20Scope.pdf|title=Wired Science! Serious Science with a Twist!|journal=Orlando Science Center Scope|date=June/July/August 2002|page=5}}</ref> Wired Science creative designers included Steve Goldman, Eileen Meier, Mark Rodriguez, and Brandy Camps. In 2003 Wired Science won the Communication Arts Magazine Award of Excellence,<ref name=CAM2003>{{cite journal|title=2003 Award of Excellence|journal=Communication Arts Magazine|date=Sep–Oct 2003|volume=Annual 9|url=http://www.stevegoldman.com/Publications/AboutWS/2003-09-00%20Communication%20Arts%20-%202003%20Award%20of%20Excellence.pdf|accessdate=2 September 2014}}</ref> the HOW Magazine Design Merit Award,<ref>{{cite journal|title=Interactive Design Competition|journal=HOW Magazine|date=August 2003|url=http://www.stevegoldman.com/Publications/AboutWS/2003-08-00%20How%20Magazine%20-%202003%20Interactive%20Design%20Competition.pdf|accessdate=2 September 2014}}</ref> and the American Advertising Federation Gold ADDY Award<ref>{{cite journal|title=Gold Addy Award|journal=ADDY|url=http://www.stevegoldman.com/Publications/AboutWS/2003-09-00%20American%20Advertising%20Federation%20-%202003%20Gold%20ADDY%20Award.pdf|accessdate=2 September 2014}}</ref> for design excellence. In 2003 Wired Science was gifted by Steve Goldman to the Orlando Science Center. Building on the experience gained from Wired Science, Why U, Inc. was founded and incorporated in 2007.
== Contributors == Why U videos are conceived and written by Steve Goldman and animated by Mark Rodriguez.
Why U videos and scripts are reviewed for correctness by mathematicians and educators from several universities, including Dr. Robert Brigham, Dr. Piotr Mikusinski, and Dr. Tammy Muhs from the [[University of Central Florida]] Mathematics Department, Dr. Mark Anderson from the [[Rollins College]] Mathematics Department, and Dr. Cheryl Avila from the [[University of Central Florida]] College of Education.
